### Move Semantics

Move semantics allow transferring resources from one object to another without copying. Introduced in C++11, it significantly improves performance for expensive-to-copy objects.

---

### Lvalues and Rvalues

```cpp
int x = 5;       // x is an lvalue (has an address)
int&& r = 5;     // 5 is an rvalue (temporary)

int getValue() { return 42; }
getValue();      // Return value is an rvalue
```

---

### Move Constructor and Move Assignment

```cpp
class Buffer {
public:
  // Move constructor
  Buffer(Buffer&& other) noexcept
    : data(other.data), size(other.size) {
    other.data = nullptr;  // Steal resource
    other.size = 0;
  }

  // Move assignment
  Buffer& operator=(Buffer&& other) noexcept {
    if (this != &other) {
      delete[] data;          // Release current
      data = other.data;      // Steal resource
      size = other.size;
      other.data = nullptr;   // Leave in valid state
      other.size = 0;
    }
    return *this;
  }
private:
  int* data;
  size_t size;
};
```

---

### std::move

Casts an lvalue to an rvalue reference:

```cpp
vector<int> v1 = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
vector<int> v2 = std::move(v1);  // Transfer ownership
// v1 is now empty (valid but unspecified state)
```

---

### std::forward (Perfect Forwarding)

```cpp
template <typename T>
void wrapper(T&& arg) {
  func(std::forward<T>(arg));  // Preserves value category
}
```

---

### When Move Happens Automatically

- Returning a local variable
- Passing a temporary to a function
- `std::move()` is called explicitly
- STL containers use move internally (e.g., `vector::push_back`)

---

> **Key Point:** Move semantics eliminate deep copying for temporary objects. Implement move constructors and move assignment operators for classes that manage resources. Mark them `noexcept` for optimal performance with STL containers.

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  vector<string> source = {"Hello", "World", "C++"};
  vector<string> dest = std::move(source);

  cout << "Source size: " << source.size() << endl;  // 0
  cout << "Dest size: " << dest.size() << endl;      // 3

  for (const string& s : dest) {
    cout << s << " ";
  }
  return 0;
}
